President Trump met with NATO Secretary General Stoltenberg in the Oval Office and praised the progress made in getting NATO allies to increase their defense spending. Trump highlighted that 7 out of the 28 NATO countries are currently meeting the 2 percent of GDP spending target, and that the US has contributed significantly to the alliance. He also emphasized the importance of fairness and burden-sharing among NATO members. Trump discussed the possibility of closing the US-Mexico border if Mexico does not take action to stop illegal immigration, expressing concern about the negative impact on the US economy but emphasizing the importance of national security. He also discussed his plans for healthcare, stating that he believes the Republican Party will become the party of healthcare and that a new healthcare package will be implemented after the 2020 election. Trump criticized Democrats for wanting to subpoena the unredacted Mueller report and stated that the investigation into the origins of the Russia investigation should be pursued.